{"title_page": "Mother of the Church", "text_new": "In [[Roman Catholic Mariology]], '''Mommy a la cheche''' (in [[Latin]] '''Mater Ecclesiae''') is a title, officially given to Mary during the [[Second Vatican Council]] by [[Pope Paul VI]]. The title was first used in the 4th century by Saint [[Ambrose of Milan]], as rediscovered by [[Hugo Rahner]].<ref name=\"HRahner\" />\n\nThe title \"Mother of the Church\" was used by Pope [[Benedict XIV]] in 1748<ref>''Bullarium Romanum,''series 2, t. 2, n. 61, p. 428</ref> and then by Pope [[Leo XIII]] in 1885.<ref>Acta Leonis XIII, 15, 302</ref> The title was also used by Pope John Paul II<ref name=\"Redemp47\">''[[Redemptoris Mater]]'' [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_25031987_redemptoris-mater_en.html Redemptoris Mather item 47 at the Vatican website]</ref> and is also found in the [[Catechism of the Catholic Church]].<ref name=\"Cat963\">\"Mary, Mother of Christ, Mother of the Church.\" [https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p123a9p6.htm Catechism item 963 at the Vatican web site]</ref>\n\nPope John Paul II stated that overall the title indicates the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]]'s maternity of Christ's faithful, as deriving from her maternity of Christ in that \"Mary is present in the Church as the Mother of Christ, and at the same time as that Mother whom Christ, in the mystery of the Redemption, gave to humanity in the person of the Apostle John [cf. John 19:27]. Thus, in her new motherhood in the Spirit, Mary embraces each and every one in the Church, and embraces each and every one through the Church.\"<ref>Pope John Paul II, Encyclical ''[[Redemptoris Mater]]'' [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_25031987_redemptoris-mater_en.html Redemeptoris Mater item 47 at the Vatican web site]</ref>\n\n==St. Ambrose and Hugo Rahner==\n{{Roman Catholic Mariology}}\nThe Church has traditionally portrayed the Blessed Virgin Mary together with the apostles and disciples gathered at that first Pentecost, joined in prayer with the first members of the Church. The title, ''Mater Ecclesiae'' is found in the writings of  Berengaud, bishop of Treves (d. 1125).<ref name=\"Mauriello\">{{Cite web |url=http://campus.udayton.edu/mary/meditations/Mchrch.html |title=Mauriello, Matthew R., \"Mary, Mother of the Church\", ''Fairfield County Catholic'', January 1996 |access-date=2016-04-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321234808/http://campus.udayton.edu/mary/meditations/Mchrch.html |archive-date=2016-03-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the 1895 encyclical ''Adjutricem populi'' (Helper of the People) Pope Leo XIII wrote, \"She is invoked as Mother of the Church and the teacher and Queen of the Apostles\". Following the title's usage by Leo XIII, it was later used many times in the teachings of [[Pope John XXIII|John XXIII]] and Paul VI,<ref>Pope John Paul II [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/audiences/1997/documents/hf_jp-ii_aud_17091997_en.html General Audience. September 17, 1997.  \"The Blessed Virgin is Mother of the Church\"], no. 2</ref> [[John Paul II]] and [[Benedict XVI]].\n\nThe use of the ''Mater Ecclesiae'' title to the Virgin Mary goes back to [[Ambrose of Milan]] in the 4th century, but this was not known until its 1944 rediscovery by [[Hugo Rahner]].<ref name=\"HRahner\" /> Rahner's Mariology,  following  Ambrose, sees Mary in her role within the Church. His interpretation, based solely on Ambrose and the [[Church Fathers|early Fathers]],<ref name=\"HRahner\">[[Hugo Rahner]], \"Mater Ecclesia - Lobpreis der Kirche aus dem ersten Jahrtausend\", Einsiedeln/K\u00f6ln 1944</ref> greatly influenced [[Vatican II]]<ref>Lumen Gentium Chapter eight,</ref> and Pope Paul VI,<ref name=\"vatican.va\">[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/paul_vi/speeches/1964/documents/hf_p-vi_spe_19641121_conclusions-iii-sessions_it.html CONCLUSIONE DELLA III SESSIONE DEL CONCILIO VATICANO II ALLOCUZIONE DEL SANTO PADRE PAOLO VI], paragraph no. 30</ref> who, quoting Ambrose, declared Mary the \"mother of the Church\".\n\n==Pope Paul VI==\n[[File:Paul VI - Official portrait.jpg|thumb|left|120px|Pope Paul VI]]\n{{quote|The Mother of the Church, carries on in heaven her maternal role with regard to the members of Christ, cooperating in the birth and development of divine life in the souls of the redeemed. - Pope Paul VI's \"Credo of the People of God\".<ref name=Credo/><ref name=Ratzinger58/>}}\nPope Paul VI pronounced the title  at the closing of the third phase of the council.<ref>Leo Cardinal Scheffczyk, Vaticanum II, in ''Remigius B\u00e4umer, Leo Scheffczyk (Hrsg.) Marienlexikon Gesamtausgabe, Institutum Marianum Regensburg'', 1994, page 568</ref> A former archbishop of [[Milan]], Paul VI used similar language to that of Saint [[Ambrose of Milan]], calling Mary ''Model of the Church'' in light of her faith, love and complete unity with Christ and ''Mother of the Church'' because she gave birth to Christ.<ref>[[Ambrose of Milan]], De inst. Virg 98, PL 16, 328 and IV, 3,4,PL17,876</ref>\n\nPaul VI made the pronouncement of the title Mother of the Church during his speech upon the closing of the third session of the Second Vatican Council on November 21, 1964: \"For the glory of the Virgin and our consolation, we proclaim Mary the Most Holy Mother of the Church, that is, the Mother of the whole People of God, both the faithful and the pastors.\"<ref name=\"vatican.va\" />\n\nIn ''[[Redemptoris Mater]]'' Pope John Paul II referred to [[Paul VI]]'s  \"Credo of the People of God\" as a reaffirmation of the statement that Mary is the \"mother of the entire Christian people, both faithful and pastors\" and wrote that the Credo \"restated this truth in an even more forceful way\":<ref name=\"Credo\">John Paul II, [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_25031987_redemptoris-mater_en.html Redemptoris Mater], no. 47, citing Pope Paul VI, Solemn Profession of Faith (30 June 1968), 15: [[Acta Apostolicae Sedis]] 60 (1968) 438f.</ref>\n\nPope Benedict XVI also referred to the ''Credo'' of Paul VI and stated that it sums up all of the scriptural texts that relate to the matter.<ref name=\"Ratzinger58\">''Mary: The Church at the Source'' by Benedict XVI, Adrian Walker and Hans Urs Von Balthasar (Oct 1, 2005) {{ISBN|158617018X}} pages 58-59</ref>\n\n==Pope John Paul II==\n[[File:Vaticano Mater Ecclesiae.jpg|thumb|Mosaic of ''Mater Ecclesiae'' in St. Peter's Square]]\nIn 1980, during the UNIV Forum,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://univforum.org/en/history|title=History {{!}} Univforum|website=univforum.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613161042/http://univforum.org/en/history|archive-date=2018-06-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> an annual gathering of university students from all over the world held in [[Rome]] during [[Holy Week]] and born by inspiration of [[Josemar\u00eda Escriv\u00e1|Saint Josemar\u00eda Escriv\u00e1]], founder of [[Opus Dei]], a young man taking part in the gathering told [[Pope John Paul II]] that he was not able to find an image of [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Our Lady]] in [[St. Peter's Square]], heart of Christendom. In fact, although there are 162 statues of saints, none of them depict the Mother of God. The Pope answered immediately: \"then we should finish the square\". When [[\u00c1lvaro del Portillo|Msgr. \u00c1lvaro del Portillo]], successor of [[Josemar\u00eda Escriv\u00e1|Saint Josemar\u00eda Escriv\u00e1]], heard this story, he asked the Spanish architect Javier Cotelo to find a good solution for the image. In July 1980 and January 1981, Cotelo submitted to the Pope a proposal of using one of the windows of the building located between [[St. Peter's Square]] and the Cortile di San Damaso, since from there the image could be seen from any part of the square. The Pope accepted the suggestion and on December 7, 1981 a mosaic of ''Maria Mater Ecclesiae'' -Our Lady, Mother of the Church- was installed following Cotelo's proposal. On the following day, feast of the [[Immaculate Conception]], the Pope blessed the mosaic from his window, and therefore this mosaic is considered to be last stone of [[St. Peter's Square]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Javier Martinez|title=La historia del mosaico de la Virgen Mar\u00eda \"Mater Ecclesia\" de la plaza de San Pedro|date=2011-07-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u00yUDAJUlU|accessdate=2018-05-20}}</ref> Moreover, this mosaic overlooking the square follows the 1981 [[Pope John Paul II assassination attempt|assassination attempt]] on [[Pope John Paul II]]'s life. It's also a tribute to the intercession of Our Lady in saving his life.\n\nIn 1987, he repeated this title ''Mother of the Church'' in his encyclical ''[[Redemptoris Mater]]'' and at a general audience on September 17, 1997.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/papaldoc/jp2bvm63.htm Blessed Virgin Is Mother Of The Church]</ref>\n\nWith regard to the title \"Mother of the Church\", John Paul used ''Redemptoris Mater'' as an opportunity to explain how the Blessed Virgin Mary's maternity of Christ's faithful derives from her maternity of Christ, as well as how Mary serves as a \"type\", or model, of the Church as a whole.\n\n:Mary is present in the Church as the Mother of Christ, and at the same time as that Mother whom Christ, in the mystery of the Redemption, gave to humanity in the person of the Apostle John. Thus, in her new motherhood in the Spirit, Mary embraces each and every one in the Church, and embraces each and every one through the Church. In this sense Mary, Mother of the Church, is also the Church's model. Indeed, as Paul VI hopes and asks, the Church must draw \"from the Virgin Mother of God the most authentic form of perfect imitation of Christ.\"<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_25031987_redemptoris-mater_en.html Redemptoris Mater], no. 47, citing Pope Paul VI, Discourse of 21 November 1964: AAS 56 (1964) 1016</ref>\n\nOn September 17, 1997, Pope John Paul II devoted a Wednesday general audience to the title \"Mother of the Church\" with regard to its application to the Blessed Virgin Mary.\n\n:The faithful first called upon Mary with the title \"Mother of God\", \"Mother of the faithful\" or \"our Mother\", to emphasize her personal relationship with each of her children.  Later, because of the greater attention paid to the mystery of the Church and to Mary\u2019s relationship to her, the Blessed Virgin began more frequently to be invoked as \"Mother of the Church\".\"<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/audiences/1997/documents/hf_jp-ii_aud_17091997_en.html John Paul II.  General Audience.  September 17, 1997.  \"Blessed Virgin is Mother of the Church,\"] no. 2</ref>\n\n:The title \"Mother of the Church\" thus reflects the deep conviction of the Christian faithful, who see in Mary not only the mother of the person of Christ, but also of the faithful.<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/audiences/1997/documents/hf_jp-ii_aud_17091997_en.html John Paul II.  General Audience. September 17, 1997.  \"The Blessed Virgin is Mother of the Church,\"] no. 5</ref>\n\n==Pope Benedict XVI==\n[[File:Barocci - Madonna del Popolo.jpg|thumb|200px|''Madonna del Popolo'' (Madonna of the people) by [[Federico Barocci]], 1579]][[Pope Benedict XVI]] addresses the issue, why [[Roman Catholic Mariology]] is related to ecclesiology, the teaching about the Church. On first sight, he argues, it may seem accidental, that the Council moved Mariology into ecclesiology. This relation helps to understand what \"Church\" really is. The theologian [[Hugo Rahner]] showed that Mariology was originally ecclesiology. The Church is like Mary.<ref name=\"Joseph Kardinal Ratzinger 2002\">Joseph Kardinal Ratzinger: Weggemeinschaft des Glaubens. Kirche als Communio. Festgabe zum 75. Geburtstag, hg. vom Sch\u00fclerkreis, Augsburg (2002)</ref>\n\nThe Church is virgin and mother, she is immaculate and carries the burdens of history. She suffers and she is assumed into heaven. Slowly she learns, that Mary is her mirror, that she is a person in Mary. Mary on the other hand is not an isolated individual, who rests in herself. She is carrying the mystery of the Church.<ref name=\"Joseph Kardinal Ratzinger 2002\"/>\n\n==Pope Francis==\nIn 2018, [[Pope Francis]] decreed that the '''Memorial of the Blessed Virgin Mary, Mother of the Church''' be inserted into the [[General Roman Calendar|Roman Calendar]] on the Monday after [[Pentecost]] (also known as [[Whit Monday]]) and to be celebrated every year.<ref>[https://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2018/03/03/0168/00350.html#ingD  \"Decreto della Congregazione per il Culto Divino e la Disciplina dei Sacramenti sulla celebrazione della beata Vergine Maria Madre della Chiesa nel Calendario Romano Generale\"]</ref>\nThe decree was signed on 11 February 2018, the memorial of [[Our Lady of Lourdes]], at the 160th anniversary of the [[Lourdes apparitions]]. It was issued on 3 March 2018.\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Mater Ecclesiae}}\n* [[Roman Catholic Mariology]]\n* [[Titles of Mary]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Virgin Mary|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mother Of The Church}}\n[[Category:Catholic Mariology]]\n[[Category:Titles of Mary]]\n", "text_old": "In [[Roman Catholic Mariology]], '''Mother of the Church''' (in [[Latin]] '''Mater Ecclesiae''') is a title, officially given to Mary during the [[Second Vatican Council]] by [[Pope Paul VI]]. The title was first used in the 4th century by Saint [[Ambrose of Milan]], as rediscovered by [[Hugo Rahner]].<ref name=\"HRahner\" />\n\nThe title \"Mother of the Church\" was used by Pope [[Benedict XIV]] in 1748<ref>''Bullarium Romanum,''series 2, t. 2, n. 61, p. 428</ref> and then by Pope [[Leo XIII]] in 1885.<ref>Acta Leonis XIII, 15, 302</ref> The title was also used by Pope John Paul II<ref name=\"Redemp47\">''[[Redemptoris Mater]]'' [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_25031987_redemptoris-mater_en.html Redemptoris Mather item 47 at the Vatican website]</ref> and is also found in the [[Catechism of the Catholic Church]].<ref name=\"Cat963\">\"Mary, Mother of Christ, Mother of the Church.\" [https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p123a9p6.htm Catechism item 963 at the Vatican web site]</ref>\n\nPope John Paul II stated that overall the title indicates the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]]'s maternity of Christ's faithful, as deriving from her maternity of Christ in that \"Mary is present in the Church as the Mother of Christ, and at the same time as that Mother whom Christ, in the mystery of the Redemption, gave to humanity in the person of the Apostle John [cf. John 19:27]. Thus, in her new motherhood in the Spirit, Mary embraces each and every one in the Church, and embraces each and every one through the Church.\"<ref>Pope John Paul II, Encyclical ''[[Redemptoris Mater]]'' [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_25031987_redemptoris-mater_en.html Redemeptoris Mater item 47 at the Vatican web site]</ref>\n\n==St. Ambrose and Hugo Rahner==\n{{Roman Catholic Mariology}}\nThe Church has traditionally portrayed the Blessed Virgin Mary together with the apostles and disciples gathered at that first Pentecost, joined in prayer with the first members of the Church. The title, ''Mater Ecclesiae'' is found in the writings of  Berengaud, bishop of Treves (d. 1125).<ref name=\"Mauriello\">{{Cite web |url=http://campus.udayton.edu/mary/meditations/Mchrch.html |title=Mauriello, Matthew R., \"Mary, Mother of the Church\", ''Fairfield County Catholic'', January 1996 |access-date=2016-04-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321234808/http://campus.udayton.edu/mary/meditations/Mchrch.html |archive-date=2016-03-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the 1895 encyclical ''Adjutricem populi'' (Helper of the People) Pope Leo XIII wrote, \"She is invoked as Mother of the Church and the teacher and Queen of the Apostles\". Following the title's usage by Leo XIII, it was later used many times in the teachings of [[Pope John XXIII|John XXIII]] and Paul VI,<ref>Pope John Paul II [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/audiences/1997/documents/hf_jp-ii_aud_17091997_en.html General Audience. September 17, 1997.  \"The Blessed Virgin is Mother of the Church\"], no. 2</ref> [[John Paul II]] and [[Benedict XVI]].\n\nThe use of the ''Mater Ecclesiae'' title to the Virgin Mary goes back to [[Ambrose of Milan]] in the 4th century, but this was not known until its 1944 rediscovery by [[Hugo Rahner]].<ref name=\"HRahner\" /> Rahner's Mariology,  following  Ambrose, sees Mary in her role within the Church. His interpretation, based solely on Ambrose and the [[Church Fathers|early Fathers]],<ref name=\"HRahner\">[[Hugo Rahner]], \"Mater Ecclesia - Lobpreis der Kirche aus dem ersten Jahrtausend\", Einsiedeln/K\u00f6ln 1944</ref> greatly influenced [[Vatican II]]<ref>Lumen Gentium Chapter eight,</ref> and Pope Paul VI,<ref name=\"vatican.va\">[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/paul_vi/speeches/1964/documents/hf_p-vi_spe_19641121_conclusions-iii-sessions_it.html CONCLUSIONE DELLA III SESSIONE DEL CONCILIO VATICANO II ALLOCUZIONE DEL SANTO PADRE PAOLO VI], paragraph no. 30</ref> who, quoting Ambrose, declared Mary the \"mother of the Church\".\n\n==Pope Paul VI==\n[[File:Paul VI - Official portrait.jpg|thumb|left|120px|Pope Paul VI]]\n{{quote|The Mother of the Church, carries on in heaven her maternal role with regard to the members of Christ, cooperating in the birth and development of divine life in the souls of the redeemed. - Pope Paul VI's \"Credo of the People of God\".<ref name=Credo/><ref name=Ratzinger58/>}}\nPope Paul VI pronounced the title  at the closing of the third phase of the council.<ref>Leo Cardinal Scheffczyk, Vaticanum II, in ''Remigius B\u00e4umer, Leo Scheffczyk (Hrsg.) Marienlexikon Gesamtausgabe, Institutum Marianum Regensburg'', 1994, page 568</ref> A former archbishop of [[Milan]], Paul VI used similar language to that of Saint [[Ambrose of Milan]], calling Mary ''Model of the Church'' in light of her faith, love and complete unity with Christ and ''Mother of the Church'' because she gave birth to Christ.<ref>[[Ambrose of Milan]], De inst. Virg 98, PL 16, 328 and IV, 3,4,PL17,876</ref>\n\nPaul VI made the pronouncement of the title Mother of the Church during his speech upon the closing of the third session of the Second Vatican Council on November 21, 1964: \"For the glory of the Virgin and our consolation, we proclaim Mary the Most Holy Mother of the Church, that is, the Mother of the whole People of God, both the faithful and the pastors.\"<ref name=\"vatican.va\" />\n\nIn ''[[Redemptoris Mater]]'' Pope John Paul II referred to [[Paul VI]]'s  \"Credo of the People of God\" as a reaffirmation of the statement that Mary is the \"mother of the entire Christian people, both faithful and pastors\" and wrote that the Credo \"restated this truth in an even more forceful way\":<ref name=\"Credo\">John Paul II, [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_25031987_redemptoris-mater_en.html Redemptoris Mater], no. 47, citing Pope Paul VI, Solemn Profession of Faith (30 June 1968), 15: [[Acta Apostolicae Sedis]] 60 (1968) 438f.</ref>\n\nPope Benedict XVI also referred to the ''Credo'' of Paul VI and stated that it sums up all of the scriptural texts that relate to the matter.<ref name=\"Ratzinger58\">''Mary: The Church at the Source'' by Benedict XVI, Adrian Walker and Hans Urs Von Balthasar (Oct 1, 2005) {{ISBN|158617018X}} pages 58-59</ref>\n\n==Pope John Paul II==\n[[File:Vaticano Mater Ecclesiae.jpg|thumb|Mosaic of ''Mater Ecclesiae'' in St. Peter's Square]]\nIn 1980, during the UNIV Forum,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://univforum.org/en/history|title=History {{!}} Univforum|website=univforum.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613161042/http://univforum.org/en/history|archive-date=2018-06-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> an annual gathering of university students from all over the world held in [[Rome]] during [[Holy Week]] and born by inspiration of [[Josemar\u00eda Escriv\u00e1|Saint Josemar\u00eda Escriv\u00e1]], founder of [[Opus Dei]], a young man taking part in the gathering told [[Pope John Paul II]] that he was not able to find an image of [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Our Lady]] in [[St. Peter's Square]], heart of Christendom. In fact, although there are 162 statues of saints, none of them depict the Mother of God. The Pope answered immediately: \"then we should finish the square\". When [[\u00c1lvaro del Portillo|Msgr. \u00c1lvaro del Portillo]], successor of [[Josemar\u00eda Escriv\u00e1|Saint Josemar\u00eda Escriv\u00e1]], heard this story, he asked the Spanish architect Javier Cotelo to find a good solution for the image. In July 1980 and January 1981, Cotelo submitted to the Pope a proposal of using one of the windows of the building located between [[St. Peter's Square]] and the Cortile di San Damaso, since from there the image could be seen from any part of the square. The Pope accepted the suggestion and on December 7, 1981 a mosaic of ''Maria Mater Ecclesiae'' -Our Lady, Mother of the Church- was installed following Cotelo's proposal. On the following day, feast of the [[Immaculate Conception]], the Pope blessed the mosaic from his window, and therefore this mosaic is considered to be last stone of [[St. Peter's Square]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Javier Martinez|title=La historia del mosaico de la Virgen Mar\u00eda \"Mater Ecclesia\" de la plaza de San Pedro|date=2011-07-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u00yUDAJUlU|accessdate=2018-05-20}}</ref> Moreover, this mosaic overlooking the square follows the 1981 [[Pope John Paul II assassination attempt|assassination attempt]] on [[Pope John Paul II]]'s life. It's also a tribute to the intercession of Our Lady in saving his life.\n\nIn 1987, he repeated this title ''Mother of the Church'' in his encyclical ''[[Redemptoris Mater]]'' and at a general audience on September 17, 1997.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/papaldoc/jp2bvm63.htm Blessed Virgin Is Mother Of The Church]</ref>\n\nWith regard to the title \"Mother of the Church\", John Paul used ''Redemptoris Mater'' as an opportunity to explain how the Blessed Virgin Mary's maternity of Christ's faithful derives from her maternity of Christ, as well as how Mary serves as a \"type\", or model, of the Church as a whole.\n\n:Mary is present in the Church as the Mother of Christ, and at the same time as that Mother whom Christ, in the mystery of the Redemption, gave to humanity in the person of the Apostle John. Thus, in her new motherhood in the Spirit, Mary embraces each and every one in the Church, and embraces each and every one through the Church. In this sense Mary, Mother of the Church, is also the Church's model. Indeed, as Paul VI hopes and asks, the Church must draw \"from the Virgin Mother of God the most authentic form of perfect imitation of Christ.\"<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_25031987_redemptoris-mater_en.html Redemptoris Mater], no. 47, citing Pope Paul VI, Discourse of 21 November 1964: AAS 56 (1964) 1016</ref>\n\nOn September 17, 1997, Pope John Paul II devoted a Wednesday general audience to the title \"Mother of the Church\" with regard to its application to the Blessed Virgin Mary.\n\n:The faithful first called upon Mary with the title \"Mother of God\", \"Mother of the faithful\" or \"our Mother\", to emphasize her personal relationship with each of her children.  Later, because of the greater attention paid to the mystery of the Church and to Mary\u2019s relationship to her, the Blessed Virgin began more frequently to be invoked as \"Mother of the Church\".\"<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/audiences/1997/documents/hf_jp-ii_aud_17091997_en.html John Paul II.  General Audience.  September 17, 1997.  \"Blessed Virgin is Mother of the Church,\"] no. 2</ref>\n\n:The title \"Mother of the Church\" thus reflects the deep conviction of the Christian faithful, who see in Mary not only the mother of the person of Christ, but also of the faithful.<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/audiences/1997/documents/hf_jp-ii_aud_17091997_en.html John Paul II.  General Audience. September 17, 1997.  \"The Blessed Virgin is Mother of the Church,\"] no. 5</ref>\n\n==Pope Benedict XVI==\n[[File:Barocci - Madonna del Popolo.jpg|thumb|200px|''Madonna del Popolo'' (Madonna of the people) by [[Federico Barocci]], 1579]][[Pope Benedict XVI]] addresses the issue, why [[Roman Catholic Mariology]] is related to ecclesiology, the teaching about the Church. On first sight, he argues, it may seem accidental, that the Council moved Mariology into ecclesiology. This relation helps to understand what \"Church\" really is. The theologian [[Hugo Rahner]] showed that Mariology was originally ecclesiology. The Church is like Mary.<ref name=\"Joseph Kardinal Ratzinger 2002\">Joseph Kardinal Ratzinger: Weggemeinschaft des Glaubens. Kirche als Communio. Festgabe zum 75. Geburtstag, hg. vom Sch\u00fclerkreis, Augsburg (2002)</ref>\n\nThe Church is virgin and mother, she is immaculate and carries the burdens of history. She suffers and she is assumed into heaven. Slowly she learns, that Mary is her mirror, that she is a person in Mary. Mary on the other hand is not an isolated individual, who rests in herself. She is carrying the mystery of the Church.<ref name=\"Joseph Kardinal Ratzinger 2002\"/>\n\n==Pope Francis==\nIn 2018, [[Pope Francis]] decreed that the '''Memorial of the Blessed Virgin Mary, Mother of the Church''' be inserted into the [[General Roman Calendar|Roman Calendar]] on the Monday after [[Pentecost]] (also known as [[Whit Monday]]) and to be celebrated every year.<ref>[https://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2018/03/03/0168/00350.html#ingD  \"Decreto della Congregazione per il Culto Divino e la Disciplina dei Sacramenti sulla celebrazione della beata Vergine Maria Madre della Chiesa nel Calendario Romano Generale\"]</ref>\nThe decree was signed on 11 February 2018, the memorial of [[Our Lady of Lourdes]], at the 160th anniversary of the [[Lourdes apparitions]]. It was issued on 3 March 2018.\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Mater Ecclesiae}}\n* [[Roman Catholic Mariology]]\n* [[Titles of Mary]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Virgin Mary|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mother Of The Church}}\n[[Category:Catholic Mariology]]\n[[Category:Titles of Mary]]\n", "name_user": "BlockEvasiion", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mother_of_the_Church"}
